{
  "id": "syntax",
  "title": "JS Syntax",
  "group": "JS Tutorial",
  "content": [
    { "type": "h1", "text": "JavaScript Syntax" },
    { "type": "p",  "text": "JavaScript syntax is the set of rules that define a correctly structured JavaScript program." },
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Values: Literals and Variables" },
    { "type": "p",  "text": "JavaScript has two types of values: fixed values (literals) and variable values (variables)." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Literals", "code": [
      "// Number literals",
      "console.log(10.5);",
      "console.log(1000);",
      "",
      "// String literals",
      "console.log(\"Hello World\");",
      "console.log('Single quotes work too');"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Variables" },
    { "type": "p",  "text": "Variables are used to store data values. JavaScript uses let, const, and var keywords to declare variables." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Variables", "code": [
      "let x = 5;",
      "let y = 6;",
      "let z = x + y;",
      "console.log(\"x + y =\", z);"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Operators and Expressions" },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Arithmetic and Assignment", "code": [
      "let a = (5 + 6) * 10;   // arithmetic",
      "console.log(a);          // 110",
      "",
      "let name = \"John\";       // assignment",
      "console.log(name);"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Case Sensitivity" },
    { "type": "p",  "text": "JavaScript is case-sensitive. Variables named lastName and lastname are different variables." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Case Sensitivity", "code": [
      "let lastName = \"Doe\";",
      "let lastname = \"Smith\";   // completely different variable!",
      "console.log(lastName);    // Doe",
      "console.log(lastname);    // Smith"
    ]},
    { "type": "h2", "text": "Naming Conventions" },
    { "type": "p",  "text": "JavaScript programmers use camelCase for variable names: firstName, masterCard, interestRate." },
    { "type": "table", "rows": [
      ["Convention",  "Example",       "Used For"],
      ["camelCase",   "firstName",     "Variables, functions (standard JS)"],
      ["PascalCase",  "FirstName",     "Classes, constructors"],
      ["UPPER_SNAKE", "MAX_SIZE",      "Constants"],
      ["underscore",  "first_name",    "Sometimes (older style)"]
    ]},
    { "type": "note", "text": "Hyphens (like first-name) are not allowed in JavaScript identifiers â€” they are reserved for subtraction." }
  ]
}
